		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><addressee>Rev. Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee> <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Albany</placeName> <date>18. December 5610</date></p>
				<p>Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Your favour from the <date>13</date> inst. was<lb/> <sic>duely</sic> <sic>recieved</sic>&#44; and I saw in it&#44; that you enjoy a good<lb/> health&#44; you are always <sic>buissy</sic>&#44; and that is all man can<lb/> ask for.  No <sic>pecuniar</sic> profit&#44; you say&#44; can be made by<lb/> the publication of my works&#44; then it shall not be published&#44;<lb/> for if it can not be sold&#44; it is certainly not worth to<lb/> be bought&#44; then it is not worth to be published&#59; and<lb/> if it be sold&#44; it must pay a little for the vast trouble<lb/> I will finish it as good as I can and also as soon<lb/> as I can.  My peculiar farce<add>&#63;</add> will I display in the<lb/> fourth maxim&#44; which shall be entirely historically<lb/> in conformity with the Prophets&#44; and in many instances<lb/> explaining them.  In this fourth maxim I will share<lb/> the historical failure of <sic>christianity</sic> on one side and<lb/> its unhistorical ground on the other side.  About the<lb/> <add>Hebrew</add> have I to remark&#44; that I can impossibly<lb/> alter the expression in this part&#44; which you have in<lb/> hand&#44; as I take the name as a foundation of the<lb/> Theology&#44; in the other parts I do not intend to mention<lb/> it.  And after all I must remark&#44; that the word<lb/> <persName>Jehovah</persName> is quite an other expression&#44; than that forbid<lb/>den one.  You write&#44; that my style is not popular<lb/> enough&#44; I tried my best to draw the <sic>Philosophie</sic><lb/> from heaven down to the earth&#59; but I can</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>2</p>
				<p>not do it any better than I did&#59; I have in the<lb/> following maxims no such high object than in the<lb/> first&#44; and can be more plain.  If the works will not find<lb/> a publisher in <placeName>America</placeName> I send it to <placeName>England</placeName>&#44; or I<lb/> translate it in the <sic>german</sic> language and send it to<lb/> my old home&#44; where it will find plenty of friends.<lb/>  I have found a young man&#44; that intends to finish<lb/> his education for the <sic>jewish</sic> ministry in my house&#44;<lb/> and he will teach in my school&#44; wherefore you may<lb/> please to leave off the advertisement.</p>
				<p>The society in <placeName>New York</placeName>&#44; which publishes the <sic>jewish</sic><lb/> <sic>cronicle</sic>&#44; has received a new supply from <placeName>England</placeName>&#44;<lb/> a young convert&#44; <persName>Joseph Levy</persName>&#44; appointed to go to<lb/> <placeName>New Orl.</placeName> paid me a visit&#44; but I did not allow him to<lb/> sit down in my house.  The man is three fourth <sic>creasy</sic><lb/> and one <sic>forth</sic> an idiot.  The <sic>jews</sic> in <placeName>Albany</placeName> find a<lb/> great deal of difficulties in the project to build a new<lb/> Synagogue&#44; and I think they will not build.</p>
				<p>You probably <sic>recieved</sic> a letter of one of my scholars&#44;<lb/> in which he wishes you to send the marks of the publication<lb/> society for our school&#45;library&#59; the boy did not know<lb/> that you resigned the office of corresp. secrty.&#44; wherefore<lb/> I must beseech you to send him or me the proper<lb/> direction of the present cor. sect.  I am curious<lb/> to read what you will say about my views on<lb/> our Theology&#44; because I am sure&#44; that if you<lb/> find fault you will say it.</p>
			<pb n="3"/>
				<p>My family is doing well&#44; and my wife sends<lb/> her best respect to you.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I am respectfully yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(3)"><persName role="author">Dr Wise</persName></p>
			<pb n="4"/>
				<p><addressee>Rev. Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)"><placeName>Walnut St.</placeName></p>
